Section 3.		The Art and Science of Reflexology
 			    by Deborah Carwana RN. RNC

Deborah is a Registered Nutritional Consultant as well as a 
registered nurse. Realizing the benefits that alternative 
treatments can offer, she has also pursued certification as 
a Reflexologist and an Aromatherapist. Deborah Carwans has her 
own health consulting business local to London, Ontario and can 
be contacted for further information or to arrange an appointment 
at:  (519)672-7997.
  
	Reflexology is a science based on the principle that there are 
reflexes in the hands and feet that corresponds to every part of the 
body. Through the application of pressure on these reflex points several
benefits can be achieved as the body's own healing powers are encouraged 
to restore and maintain health and well-being, naturally.

	Reflexology reflects the idea that natural life energy flows 
through our body along zones or meridians running the length of the 
body from head to toe to reflexes in the hands and feet, and all the 
organs and parts of the body lie along one or more of these zones.
	
	Stress and tension cause blockages or congestion along these 
zones, circulation becomes sluggish, blood and oxygen supply to every 
cell is decreased and our bodies re no longer functioning optimally - 
we are no longer in balance. This imbalance can manifest itself as a 
tender spot on the foot signaling that the corresponding area of the 
body may not be operating at peak performance.

	It has been suggested that 75% of all illness and dis-ease is a 
result of the stress we live with. A reflexology treatment provides 
deep relaxation, a release of tension, improved circulation and, 
theoretically, an opportunity to cleanse the body of toxins and 
impurities.

	Reflexology is effective and helpful in normalizing many 
different body conditions. For many people reflexology has been 
helpful for painful, chronic conditions such as arthritis, headaches 
and insomnia. Women have found childbirth easier - labour is shorter 
with less discomfort when receiving reflexology for a period of time 
before the birth. It is also very supportive for the post-natal period.

	The reflexology session takes place in a safe, quiet and relaxing 
area. You are usually positioned in a reclining chair or on a therapy 
table. The reflexologist works on your bare feet and the session usually 
begins with a series of warm-up exercises. All the reflex points on both 
feet are worked using finger and thumb pressure. A complete treatment is 
always given as the body is to be considered holistically. The session 
ends with a relaxing foot rub using lotion or oil.

	Reflexology will not harm you in any way; it simply brings your 
system back into balance. Clients report a range of experiences after a
treatment from deep relaxation and tranquillity to a feeling of being 
centered and focused. There is a sense of rejuvenation and renewed energy. 
Many people fall asleep during a treatment or find that their sleep 
improves at night. A session usually lasts about 45 minutes to an hour. 
(For babies, the elderly or extremely ill the length of the session and 
the pressure applied is decreased.) For acute conditions a treatment can 
be given every 48 hours. For chronic conditions weekly sessions are 
recommended. Monthly treatments are used for prevention, maintenance 
and general relaxation.

	It is interesting to note that in Denmark, Reflexology is the 
most common alternative treatment used. 1 out of every 4 Danes chooses
reflexology as the preferred health care treatment. There is also 
emphasis on researching the efficacy of reflexology in the workplace 
where back pain, sore muscles and aches are common. The results are very
positive; showing a decreased in work hours lost which translates into 
dollars saved. As a result reflexologists are being hired to work for 
many different companies as part of their wellness programs.

