Section 4.			Stopped Cold: 
Echinacea Is The Hot New Remedy That Has Herbal Medicine Fans All Atingle 

                     	By Tracy L. Pipp 
				The Detroit News 
			Wednesday, February 19, 1997 

Many people don't know where it comes from. Not everybody can spell it. 
But that doesn't stop them from taking echinacea, the hottest herbal 
remedy around. It's become as acceptable as vitamin C for fighting off 
the common cold. Users swear that taking echinacea at the onset of a 
sore throat or runny nose lessens the severity and duration of their 
symptoms. Not a bad reputation for an herb with a name that's dauntingly
unpronounceable. 

Echinacea (eck-in-ASIA) used to cower in the dark corners of nutrition 
and health food stores. But its newfound popularity means you can now 
find bottles of it at your local drugstore. "A few years ago, no one 
had heard of it," says Marguerite Smith of NutriLite products. "It wasn't 
even mentioned in the industry top 10 list of what people were buying. 
Now it's selling like crazy." 
               
Echinacea was used by Native Americans for generations to treat a variety 
of ailments -- everything from snakebites,  toothaches and coughs to
inflammations and infections. Today, researchers concur that echinacea 
can reduce swelling and has prominent antibiotic and antiviral properties. 
The renewed interest in the extract of the coneflower is due to 
echinacea's role as an immune system stimulant. "There's a well-documented
history of echinacea's power to boost the immune system and its ability to 
treat a wide variety of conditions," says Wayne Silverman of the American
Botanical Council. And, judging by sales, lots of Americans are trying it 
out. "It's consistently one of our most popular products," says Stacey 
Hessen, manager of Betty's Grocery Store in Birmingham. The store sells it 
as a tincture and in capsule form In liquid form, it should tingle on your
tongue -- if it doesn't, the active ingredient is too diluted to be 
effective. And it's better to take it only when you need it, for no longer 
than a week at a time: Various studies indicate that echinacea is most 
effective when it is only taken when sick and not used as a preventive 
measure. 

Dr. Charles McCloskey, director of outpatient care at Oakland General 
Hospital in Madison Heights, says several German studies indicate that 
echinacea does indeed strengthen the immune but that no such studies have 
been done in the United States. But despite the lack of U.S.-based 
evidence, "some patients swear by it," he says. 

Some of echinacea's allure stems from its natural origin and its lack of 
side effects, McCloskey says. "I don't know anyone who has overdosed on
it." This mainstream popularity is sparking new interest in herbal
remedies, and experts believe the success of echinacea could be just the
thing to clear 
a path for other herbs and natural fix-its.

