Section 5.	       The Bath - A Place To Honour Ourselves
				by Deborah Carwana RN. RNC

Deborah is a Registered Nutritional Consultant as well as a registered 
nurse. Realizing the benefits that alternative treatments can offer, 
she has also pursued certification as a Reflexologist and an 
Aromatherapist. Deborah Carwans has her own health consulting business 
local to London, Ontario and can be contacted for further information 
or to arrange an appointment at:  (519)672-7997.

	Aromatherapy: a natural healing art that uses richly aromatic 
oils extracted from plants to tone and regulate the body, and ease the 
mind and spirits. The effect can be either relaxing or stimulating and
refreshing depending on what oils are used. Modern research has proven 
the health-giving qualities of different plant essences, for example 
the antiseptic properties of tea-tree, the soothing effects of lavender, 
and the head clearing properties of eucalyptus. The therapeutic effect 
of these oils is achieved either by inhalation or absorption through the 
skin. They can be mixed into ointments and lotions, in bath or massage 
oils, on compresses or in vaporizers. Blending them together in different
combinations will give the best results. For example, an invigorating 
blend of basil and rosemary can be used in a vaporizer in the workplace 
or home to enhance memory and stimulate the mind. Insomnia can be overcome 
with a warm soothing bath to which a blend of lavender and sandalwood has 
been added or with a few drops of essential oil of neroli on your pillow.
	
	The hectic lifestyles of the 90's have encouraged many of us to 
turn to a shower for daily hygiene and the bath has been relegated for 
the use of the infirm and children. But what a waste of an accessible 
tool for our own wellness. A bath allows a retreat. A place where we can 
honour ourselves, our bodies, and by using essential oils in our bath, 
enhance our physical, mental, emotional and spiritual well being.
	
	A further benefit of the aromatic bath is that the essential oils 
do not remain in the body, unlike some chemical drugs, and depending on 
the oil used and the health of the body, will be totally expelled in 
between three and fourteen hours.

	The easiest way to add essential oils to the bath is to completely 
pour the bath and, just as you are getting into in add 8 to 10 drops of an
essential oil. In this way you will receive all the benefits of the 
essential oil inhaled. Another method is to first add a carrier oil, such 
as sweet almond or apricot kernel oil to your blend of essential oils and 
then add to your bath. This is much more luxurious and combats any 
tendency to dry skin. One can create blends to reduce stress, to 
revitalize yourself after a tough day, and to address specific physical
concerns.

	An added benefit to your aromatherapy bath would be to combine it 
with a massage. In aroma-massage the therapist gently massages the 
essential oils which are diluted in a carrier oil into your skin. For 
those who want a more therapeutic bath and to eliminate toxins, a blend 
of essential oils can be ground into a base of mineral/Epsom salts… a 
wonderful tonic to start or end the day.

	There are always precautions when using essential oils. Oils of 
cinnamon, clove, basil, peppermint, thyme, wintergreen or sassafras 
should never be used in a bath as they may irritate your skin. Pregnant 
women and people with epilepsy should consult with an aromatherapist 
before using any essential oil or blend of oils. Those used with children 
should be diluted four times the adult formulation and should be made 
from only the gentlest of oils (neroli, rose) and never used without a 
carrier oil.

	Whether you choose an aromatic bath for romance or to nurture 
health and well being, the combination of water and oil is a delightful 
mix.

