			Hope For Migraine Sufferers

	For those who suffer from migraine headaches, there may be new 
hope. The November/December issue of Health magazine reported that a 
Belgian study showed vitamin B2, or riboflavin, "remarkably reduces the 
number and intensity of migraines."
	"Forty-eight migraine patients were divided into two groups. The 
first group received 400 milligrams of riboflavin every morning in a 
single dose - the equivalent of sitting down to 600 bowls of Cheerios 
with milk. The second group received the same amount of riboflavin along 
with 75 milligrams of aspirin. This treatment continued for three to five
months. At the end of the study, nearly 80 percent of all patients had 
fewer than half the number of migrain days they had experienced before
treatment, and the severity of the headaches was reduced by about 
two-thirds. The aspirin apparently provided no additional relief."
	The report goes on to say that researchers are hoping their results 
can be duplicated, even with a lower dose of riboflavin.
			(Health, November/December 1995)

